<div id="review_3240808973" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3240808973" />
    <a title="Sara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5722821-sara"><img alt="Sara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1324478680p2/5722821.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3240808973?book_show_action=true">Dec 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sara" href="/user/show/5722821-sara">Sara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3240808973" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3214833650670193872">This is a grounding, generous-hearted book perfect for the come-down from a huge spiritual experience. It reminds us that all people--and especially those who&apos;ve dedicated themselves to spirituality--are still messy humans, and that compassion and acceptance is meant to be practiced not just on retreat or on the cushion, but in our regular, everyday lives. Kornfield manages to instill forgiveness for one&apos;s all too human foibles, while still holding unethical spiritual leaders (such as those who </span>
  <span id="freeText3214833650670193872" style="display:none">This is a grounding, generous-hearted book perfect for the come-down from a huge spiritual experience. It reminds us that all people--and especially those who've dedicated themselves to spirituality--are still messy humans, and that compassion and acceptance is meant to be practiced not just on retreat or on the cushion, but in our regular, everyday lives. Kornfield manages to instill forgiveness for one's all too human foibles, while still holding unethical spiritual leaders (such as those who sexually abuse their students) responsible for their actions. If you've ever felt bad for getting mad or confused, even after you've seen the face of your God of choice, then this book is for you.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3214833650670193872" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


